         FOR WHOM
    ===================================================================== -->
    <section class="mb-20">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 text-accent">For whom</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-muted">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-warm">→</span> Builders of multi-step agent workflows that don't fit in one context window</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-warm">→</span> Anyone running Claude Code, Codex, ollama, or similar long-running LLM agents at scale</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-warm">→</span> Teams shipping agent-driven pipelines that need to survive compaction, rate limits, restarts</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-warm">→</span> Cross-tool federation: Claude + n8n + cron + shell, all writing to the same substrate</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-warm">→</span> Anyone tired of treating chat history as state</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- ====================================================================
         ARCHITECTURE PRINCIPLE
    ===================================================================== -->
    <section class="mb-20">
      <div class="bg-panel border-l-4 border-accent p-8 rounded-r">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">The file system IS the orchestrator</h3>
        <p class="text-muted leading-relaxed">
          No daemon. No broker. No external database. Just directory layout + POSIX atomic rename + JSON files. Any agent with read/write access is a participant. UNIX shops have done this for 30 years — Maildir (1995), cron + lock files, <code class="bg-code-bg border border-code-border px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm">/var/spool/</code>. swarm-lib applies the discipline to LLM-driven agent work.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

